# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-california-riverside
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Rio de Janeiro was announced as the host city at the 121st IOC Session in Copenhagen, Denmark, on 2 October 2009.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] 11,238 athletes from 207 nations took part in the 2016 Games, including first-time entrants Kosovo, South Sudan, and the Refugee Olympic Team.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] With 306 sets of medals, the Games featured 28 Olympic sports, including rugby sevens and golf, which were added to the Olympic program in 2009.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] These sporting events took place at 33 venues in the host city and at five separate venues in the Brazilian cities of São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, Salvador, Brasília, and Manaus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] These were also the first Summer Olympics to take place under the International Olympic Committee (IOC) presidency of Thomas Bach.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The games were opened by acting president of Brazil (and later president), Michel Temer and closed by Bach.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table, winning the most gold medals (46) and the highest number of medals overall (121); the U.S. team also won its 1,000th Summer Olympic gold medal.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Great Britain finished second and the only country to increase its tally of medals in the Summer Olympiad immediately after being the host nation.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Host nation Brazil won seven gold medals and 19 total medals, its best result at any Olympics, finishing in thirteenth place.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Bahrain, Fiji, Ivory Coast, Jordan, Kosovo, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Tajikistan, and Vietnam all won their first gold medals, as did the group of Independent Olympic Athletes (from Kuwait).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The bidding process for the 2016 Summer Olympics was officially launched on 16 May 2007.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The first step for each city was to submit an initial application to the International Olympic Committee by 13 September 2007, confirming their intention to bid.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Completed official bid files containing answers to a 25-question IOC form were to be submitted by each city by the deadline of 14 January 2008.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] On 4 June 2008, two months before the Beijing Olympics, four candidate cities were chosen for the shortlist: Chicago, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro, and Tokyo, which had already hosted the Summer Olympics in 1964.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Three cities—Baku, Doha, and Prague—failed to reach the candidature phase.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Nawal El Moutawakel of Morocco headed the 10-member Evaluation Commission, having also chaired the evaluation commission for the 2012 Summer Olympics bids, which was awarded to London, United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The commission made on-site inspections in the second quarter of 2009.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] They issued a comprehensive technical appraisal for IOC members on 2 September, one month before the elections.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Many safeguards were put in place to prevent bidding cities from communicating with or directly influencing the 115 IOC members eligible to vote in the elections.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] For example, cities could not invite any IOC member to visit, nor could they send anything that could be construed as a gift.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Nonetheless, bidding cities invested large sums in their PR and media programs to indirectly influence the IOC members by garnering domestic support and backing from sports media and general international media.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The final voting was held in Copenhagen on 2 October 2009, with Madrid and Rio de Janeiro considered favorites to secure the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Chicago was eliminated after the first round of voting, and Tokyo after the second (The latter city would eventually be awarded the 2020 Summer Olympics in 2013).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Rio de Janeiro took a significant lead over Madrid, heading into the final round; the lead was held, and Rio de Janeiro was announced as host of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] On 26 June 2011, it was reported on Around The Rings that Roderlei Generali, the COO of the Rio de Janeiro Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games, resigned just one year after taking the job at ROOC.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] This came just five months after CCO Flávio Pestana quit for personal reasons.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Pestana withdrew later during the 2012 Summer Paralympics, and Renato Ciuchin was then appointed as COO.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Events took place at eighteen existing venues, nine new venues constructed specifically for the Games, and seven temporary venues.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] For the events held in Rio de Janeiro, each event was held in one of four geographically segregated Olympic clusters–Barra, Copacabana, Deodoro, and Maracanã–as was done for the 2007 Pan American Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Several of the venues were located at the Barra Cluster Olympic Park.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Nearly half of the athletes could reach their venues in less than 10 minutes, and almost 75 per cent could do so in less than 25 minutes.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Of the 34 competition venues, eight underwent some permanent works, seven were totally temporary and nine were constructed as permanent legacy venues.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The largest venue at the Games in terms of seating capacity was the 75,000-seat Maracanã Stadium, which served as the ceremonies venue and site of the football finals.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The second largest stadium was the 60,000-seat Estádio Olímpico Nilton Santos (formerly João Havelange during the Games), which hosted track and field events.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The athletes' village was said to be the largest in Olympic history.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Barra Olympic Park is a cluster of nine sporting venues in Barra da Tijuca, in the west zone of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The site was formerly occupied by the Autódromo Internacional Nelson Piquet, also known as the Jacarepaguá Formula One circuit.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] As well as the Estádio Olímpico João Havelange and Maracanã and in Rio de Janeiro, football matches took place at five venues in the cities of São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, and the more distant Salvador, Brasília and Manaus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Rio's historical downtown underwent an urban waterfront revitalization project known as *Porto Maravilha*, covering 5 km2 (1.9 mi2) in area.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The project aimed to redevelop the port area, increase the city center's attractiveness, and enhance Rio's competitive position in the global economy.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The urban renovation involved 700 km (430 mi) of public networks for water supply, sanitation, drainage, electricity, gas and telecom; 4 km (2.5 mi) of tunnels; 70 km (43 mi) of roads; 650 km2 (250 mi2) of sidewalks; 17 km (11 mi) of bike path; 15,000 trees; and three sanitation treatment plants.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] As part of this renovation, a new tram was built from the Santos Dumont Airport to Rodoviária Novo Rio, due to open in April 2016.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Games required over 200 kilometers of security fencing.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A 15,000 square meter warehouse in Barra da Tijuca was used to assemble and supply the furniture and fittings for the Olympic Village.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The second warehouse of 90,000 square meters in Duque de Caxias, near the roads that provide access to the venues, contained all the equipment needed for the sporting events.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The medals were produced by the Casa da Moeda do Brasil (the Brazilian National Mint).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The medal design was unveiled on 15 June 2016.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] They were designed to be environmentally friendly using recycled materials; the bronze and silver medals contained 30% recycled materials.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The gold medals were produced using gold that had been mined and extracted according to a set of sustainability criteria, such as being extracted without the use of mercury.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The medals feature a wreath design on the front, and in keeping with tradition, the obverse features Nike, the Greek goddess of victory.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A wooden carrying box accompanied each medal.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Medalists were also awarded a trophy in the shape of the Games' emblem.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In May 2017, an Associated Press article disclosed that over 100 athletes who had won medals at the Rio Olympics reported that their medals were showing some damage, including black spots, flaking, or surface degrading.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Rio officials offered to replace any defective medals and found problems with 6 to 7 percent of all those awarded.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Rio 2016 podiums featured designs and vegetation reminiscent of the city of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The podiums were made from wood and adorned with foliage in keeping with the natural “Look” of the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] They also needed to be light enough to be easily carried and assembled, but also strong enough to support up to 18 athletes on each stand.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The blue, green, yellow and orange colours that feature on the podium were symbolic of the Games' visual identity, inspired by Brazil’s harmonic diversity.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] All materials were organic and celebrated the tropical nature of Brazil, with the intent to be reused as furniture after the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] After the games, the podium from the Brazilian national football team's Olympic gold medal, that was 12 meters wide, was being auctioned off.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] It was divided into five parts, with values ranging from R$ 505,00 to R$ 925,00.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In the end, it was businessman Sérgio Santos who ended up buying the piece.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Olympic flame was lit on 21 April 2016 at the Temple of Hera in Olympia, the traditional start of the Greek phase of the torch relay.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The flame was handed over to the Brazilian organisers in a ceremony at the Panathenaic Stadium in Athens on 27 April.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A brief stop-off was made in Switzerland to visit the IOC headquarters and the Olympic Museum in Lausanne, as well as the United Nations Office at Geneva.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The torch relay began its journey around Brazil on 3 May at the capital Brasília.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The flame visited more than 300 Brazilian cities, including all 26 state capitals and the Brazilian Federal District.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The relay ended in Rio de Janeiro on 5 August when the flame was used to light the Olympic cauldron during the opening ceremony.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Unpaid volunteers performed a variety of tasks before and during the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A target of 50,000 volunteers was set as early as 2012.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] More than 240,000 applications were received when recruitment took place in 2014.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The clothing worn by the volunteers included yellow polo shirts and jackets, beige trousers, white socks, and green trainers, which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Volunteers also wore photo accreditation badges which were allocated to officials, athletes, family members, and media, allowing them to gain access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Many volunteers gave up their roles due to long working hours and insufficient free meals.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The ticket prices were announced on 16 September 2014, all of which were sold in Brazilian reais (BRL).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A total of 7.5 million tickets were to be sold in total, with ticket prices ranging from BRL 40 for many events to BRL 4,600 for the most expensive seats at the opening ceremony.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] About 3.8 million of these tickets were available for BRL 70 or less.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] As an aspect of its bid, Rio's organizing committee planned to focus on sustainability and environmental protection as a theme of the 2016 Games, going on to dub them a "Green Games for a Blue Planet".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] However, some of these projects met with delays or faced economic shortfalls, leading some critics to believe that Rio would not be able to accomplish them.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The focus on environmental protection also influenced the implementation of certain Olympic protocols.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] To reduce emissions, the Olympic cauldron was designed to be smaller than previous iterations, using a kinetic sculpture to enhance its appearance in place of a larger body of flames.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The bronze and silver medals, as well as the ribbons on all medals, were designed to incorporate recycled materials.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The athletes were not presented with flowers during the medal ceremonies, as had been the tradition at previous Olympics (although floral displays were still used as part of the staging of medal presentations).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The organizers considered the practice to be wasteful because the flowers were often thrown away and "would struggle to survive in the tropical Brazilian climate" if kept.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The podiums were designed using materials that could be recycled to make furniture.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Future Arena, the venue for the handball competitions, was designed as a temporary modular structure whose components could be reconstructed after the Games to build schools.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] However, as of November 2017, the arena was still standing due to lack of funds to dismantle it and no allocation of funds to do so in the 2018 budget.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Portions of the opening ceremony were dedicated to the issue of climate change.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony took place at Maracanã Stadium on 5 August 2016, directed by Fernando Meirelles, Daniela Thomas, and Andrucha Waddington.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The ceremony highlighted aspects of Brazilian history and culture, and featured a segment narrated by Fernanda Montenegro and Judi Dench with an appeal to environmental conservation and the prevention of global warming.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The crowd in the stadium numbered 60,000 and the event was broadcast to an estimated global audience of three billion.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The ceremony included the inaugural presentation of the Olympic Laurel, an honor bestowed by the IOC on those that have made "significant achievements in education, culture, development and peace through sport"; the trophy was awarded to Kenyan athlete Kipchoge Keino.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Games were officially opened by the acting president of Brazil, Michel Temer.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Olympic cauldron was lit by long-distance runner Vanderlei Cordeiro de Lima, the men's marathon bronze medalist at the 2004 Olympics, who had also received the IOC's Pierre de Coubertin medal for sportsmanship after being attacked by a spectator and losing his lead in the race.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The cauldron was originally expected to be lit by Brazilian footballer Pelé, but he declined to participate due to health problems.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Following the opening ceremony, a public cauldron was lit in front of the Candelária Church by Jorge Gomes, a 14-year-old Brazilian athlete who had escaped from poverty to train as a runner.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The 2016 Summer Olympic program featured 28 sports encompassing 306 medal events.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The number of events in each of 42 discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In April 2008, the IOC began accepting applications for two new sports to be introduced to the Olympic programme.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Baseball and softball (which were both dropped in 2005), karate, squash, golf, roller sports, and rugby union all applied to be included on the programme.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Formal presentations were made to the IOC executive board in June 2009.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In August, the executive board initially gave its approval to rugby sevens—a seven-player version of rugby union—by a majority vote; baseball/softball, roller sports, and squash were removed from contention, leaving golf, karate, and rugby sevens in the running.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A final vote was held on 9 October 2009, the closing day of the 121st IOC Session.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] At this session, a new voting system was in place: a sport now needed only a simple majority from the full IOC committee for approval rather than the two-thirds majority previously required.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The 121st IOC Session decided to add rugby sevens and golf to the Rio 2016 Olympic programme.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The tally for rugby was 81 in favor, with eight against, and golf was approved by 63 votes to 26.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Neither of these two sports was new to the Summer Olympics; rugby last featured in 1924, and golf in 1904.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In May 2012, the International Sailing Federation announced that windsurfing would be replaced by kitesurfing at the 2016 Olympics, but this decision was reversed in November.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Twenty-seven world records and ninety-one Olympic records were set during the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The records were set in archery, athletics, canoeing, cycling track, modern pentathlon, rowing, shooting, swimming, and weightlifting.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] A number of events, most notably in aquatics, beach volleyball and track and field, were scheduled with sessions and matches occurring as late as 10:00 p.m. to midnight BRT.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] As Brasília time is only one hour ahead of the U.S.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Eastern Time Zone, certain marquee events were scheduled to occur during U.S. primetime hours (traditionally 8:00 to 11:00 p.m.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] ET, 9:00 p.m. to midnight BRT), allowing them to be broadcast live on the east coast as opposed to being delayed.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] This practice was also beneficial to Globo; a Brazilian critic noted that the network very rarely preempts its primetime telenovelas, as they are among the highest-rated programs in the country.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony of the 2016 Summer Olympics was held on 21 August 2016 from 20:00 to 22:50 BRT at the Maracanã Stadium.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The creative director for the ceremony was Rosa Magalhães.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Amid heavy rainfall, the ceremony began with interpretive dancers representing various landmarks in the host city.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Martinho da Vila then performed a rendition of "Carinhoso" by Pixinguinha.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In another segment, introducing the athletes, singer Roberta Sá channeled Carmen Miranda, the fruit-headdress-wearing, mid-century Hollywood diva who endures as a beloved camp figure.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Parade of Flags followed shortly after a choir of 27 children, representing the states of Brazil, sang the Brazilian national anthem.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Oxford Olympics Study 2016 estimated the out-turn cost of the Rio 2016 Summer Olympics at US$4.6 billion in 2015-dollars.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Indirect capital costs were not included, such as for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, for hotel upgrades, or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Rio Olympics' cost of US$4.6 billion compares with costs of US$40–44 billion for Beijing 2008 and US$51 billion for Sochi 2014, the two most expensive Olympics in history.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The average cost of the Summer Games since 1960 is US$5.2 billion.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] All 205 National Olympic Committees qualified at least one athlete.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The first three nations to qualify athletes for the Games were Germany, Great Britain, and the Netherlands, who each qualified four athletes for the team dressage by winning medals in the team event at the 2014 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] As host nation, Brazil received automatic entry for some sports including in all cycling disciplines and six places for weightlifting events.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The 2016 Summer Olympics were the first Games in which Kosovo and South Sudan were eligible to participate.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Bulgarian and Russian weightlifters were banned from Rio Olympics for numerous anti-doping violations.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Kuwait was banned in October 2015 for the second time in five years over government interference in the country's Olympic committee.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Kuwaiti athletes instead participated as "Independent Olympic Athletes".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Due to the European migrant crisis and other reasons, the IOC allowed athletes to compete as Independent Olympians under the Olympic Flag.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] During the previous Summer Olympic Games, refugees were ineligible to compete because of their inability to represent their home NOCs.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] On 2 March 2016, the IOC finalized plans for a specific Refugee Olympic Team (ROT); out of 43 refugee athletes deemed potentially eligible, 10 were chosen to form the team.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Due to the suspension of the National Olympic Committee of Kuwait, participants from Kuwait were allowed to participate under the Olympic Flag as Independent Olympic Athletes.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In November 2015, Russia was provisionally suspended from all international track and field athletic competitions by the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) following a World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) report into a doping program in the country.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The IAAF announced that it would allow individual Russian athletes to apply for "exceptional eligibility" to participate in the Games as "neutral" athletes if it was independently verified that they had not engaged in doping nor in the Russian doping program.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] On 24 July 2016, the IOC rejected the IAAF and WADA's recommendations to allow athletes to compete neutrally, stating that the Olympic Charter "does not foresee such 'neutral athletes'" and that it was each country's National Olympic Committee decision on which athletes would be competing.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] As a result, Russian athletes competed under the Russian flag, although they would compete under a neutral flag in the 2018 Winter Olympics following several developments concerning the doping investigation.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] During the Games, some countries and continents had a national house.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] These temporary meeting places for supporters, athletes and other followers were located throughout Rio de Janeiro.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] This is currently based on the schedule released on the same day as ticket sales began, 31 March 2015.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The top ten listed NOCs by the number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Host nation Brazil finished in 13th place with a total of 19 medals (7 gold, 6 silver, and 6 bronze).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Olympic Broadcasting Services served as the host broadcaster for the 2016 Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Produced from a total of seven mobile units, OBS distributed 40,000 hours of television footage and 60,000 hours of digital footage of the Games to its international rightsholders.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, digital-oriented footage exceeded the amount of television-oriented footage.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed in the Barra da Tijuca cluster.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] NHK and OBS once again filmed portions of the Games, including the opening ceremony and selected events, in 8K resolution video.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Additionally, expanding upon a 180-degree trial at the 2016 Winter Youth Olympics, 85 hours of video content were originated in 360-degree virtual reality formats.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In the United States, NBCUniversal offered 4K content downconverted from the 8K footage and with HDR and Dolby Atmos support, to participating television providers.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Owing to their expertise in domestic broadcasts of the new sports introduced in Rio, NBCU and Sky New Zealand staff handled the production of the golf and rugby sevens events on behalf of OBS.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In August 2009, the IOC reached a deal to sell domestic broadcast rights for the 2016 Summer Olympics to Grupo Globo.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Replacing Record, the deal covers free-to-air coverage on Rede Globo, pay TV, and digital rights to the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In turn, Globo sublicensed partial free-to-air rights to Record, along with Band.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] IOC board member Richard Carrión described the agreement as "unprecedented", touting that "by working with Brazil's leading media organizations, we are confident that this represents a great deal for Olympic fans in the region.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] In November 2017, the International Olympic Committee announced the winners of the Golden rings in six categories for the best broadcast coverage of the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Sports Production was awarded to Beach Volleyball, produced by Geoff Johnson and directed by Greg Breakell and Gary Milkis.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The production for the cycling road race and Sailing came second and third.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The next category was the best Olympic feature, for which TV Globo's show *Esporte Espetacular* finished third, and CCTV China's feature *A Sequel of Love* came second.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The winner was NBC Olympics for their feature *The Most Beautiful Thing*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The third category was The Best Athlete Profile, for which RTBF from Belgium collected the third place prize for their profile of Nafi Thiam.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Globo went one better than the previous category coming second with their profile of Isaquias Queiroz.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The winner of the category again was NBC, this time for their piece on Wayde van Niekerk.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Best On-Air Promotion was announced next, with the BBC Sport winning with NBC coming second this time and BNT from Bulgaria finishing third.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Digital Service went to NBC, with ZDF and SporTV/Globosat picking up the second and third places.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Programme was awarded to SporTV/Globosat, while TV Globo and BBC Sport completed the podium.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] On 24 November 2014, the official mascots of the 2016 Summer Olympics and Paralympics were unveiled, created by São Paulo-based animation company Birdo.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The Olympic mascot Vinicius, named after musician Vinicius de Moraes, represents Brazilian wildlife and carries design traits of cats, monkeys, and birds.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] According to their fictional backgrounds, the mascots "were both born from the joy of Brazilians after it was announced that Rio would host the Games".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Brand director Beth Lula stated that the mascots were intended to reflect the diversity of Brazil's culture and people.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The names of the mascots were determined by a public vote whose results were announced on 14 December 2014.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The names, which reference the co-writers of the song "The Girl from Ipanema", won over two other sets of names, tallying 44 percent of 323,327 votes.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] At the Olympic wrestling events, coaches were given plush dolls of Vinicius to throw into the ring when they wished to challenge a referee's call.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The official emblem for the 2016 Summer Olympics was designed by Brazilian agency Tatíl Design and was unveiled on 31 December 2010, winning in a competition against 139 agencies.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The emblem represents three figures joined at their arms and feet, with the overall shape reflecting that of Sugarloaf Mountain.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] It was also designed to have a three-dimensional form, which designer Fred Gelli claimed made it the first 3D logo in the history of the Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] The logo has been noted as evoking Henri Matisse's painting *Dance*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] There were also allegations by the Colorado-based Telluride Foundation that the logo had been plagiarized from its own; while also consisting of several figures linked in motion, the Telluride Foundation logo contains four figures.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] This was not the first time that the foundation had alleged plagiarism of its logo by a Brazilian event; in 2004, the linked figures element had been copied for the logo of Carnival celebrations in Salvador.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Gelli defended the allegations, stating that the concept of figures linked in embrace was not inherently original, as it was "an ancient reference" and "in the collective unconscious".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p01] Gelli cited *Dance* as an influence of the logo's concept and stated that the designers had intentionally aimed to make the interpretation of the concept as dissimilar to others as possible.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] However, the Zika virus was not contracted by anyone competing in or attending the Olympics, and the Games went ahead normally with no major incident.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] There is no legally legitimate evidence of impropriety in the choice of Rio to host the Olympic games, at least as far as the Brazilian Olympic Committee or the politicians involved in the process are concerned.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] However, the specialized media raised suspicions about it.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In 2014, Operation Car Wash, an investigation by the Federal Police of Brazil, uncovered unprecedented money laundering and corruption at the state-controlled oil company Petrobras.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In early 2015, a series of protests against alleged corruption by the government of President Dilma Rousseff began in Brazil, triggered by revelations that numerous politicians were involved in the Petrobras affair.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] By early 2016, the scandal had escalated into a full-blown political crisis affecting not only President Rousseff, but also former President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, resulting in widespread demonstrations involving millions of protesters, both anti- and pro-Rousseff.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] At the same time, Brazil faced its worst economic recession since the 1990s, raising questions about whether the country was adequately prepared to host the Olympic Games against a volatile political and economic backdrop.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] On 12 May 2016, President Rousseff was stripped of her powers and duties for 180 days after an impeachment vote in the Federal Senate, with Vice President Michel Temer standing in as acting president during the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] On 5 October 2017, Brazilian Olympic Committee head Carlos Nuzman was arrested amid a money-laundering investigation into a $2 million payment that was allegedly made to secure votes for the bid to bring the Olympics to Rio.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The money was believed to have been paid to former IAAF president Lamine Diack and his son Papa Massata Diack, who was a member of the IOC at the time of the alleged payment, which was three days before the vote in 2009.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] All three were charged with money laundering, along with the former Rio state governor Sérgio Cabral Filho (who was already in prison for money laundering offenses at the time), Brazilian businessman Arthur Soares, and ex-Brazilian Olympic Committee chief Leonardo Gryner.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] All six were charged with running a criminal organization, money laundering, and violating currency laws in their own native countries.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] On 4 July 2019, it was reported that Cabral told a judge that the money paid to Diack was used to buy as many as nine votes.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Rio mayor Eduardo Paes was also accused of corruption and fraud in relation to the construction of a number of venues for the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In 2024, Nuzman's and Cabral's conviction in this legal case was overturned by the Court.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] An outbreak of the mosquito-borne Zika virus in Brazil raised fears regarding its potential impact on athletes and visitors.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] To prevent puddles of stagnant water that allow mosquitoes to breed, organizers announced plans to perform daily inspections of Olympic venues.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Zika virus transmission was also attributed to inefficient sewage treatment in the area, an issue that was also in the process of being addressed for the Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In May 2016, a group of 150 physicians and scientists sent an open letter to the World Health Organization (WHO), calling upon them to, according to co-author Arthur Caplan, have "an open, transparent discussion of the risks of holding the Olympics as planned in Brazil".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The WHO dismissed the request, stating that "cancelling or changing the location of the 2016 Olympics [would] not significantly alter the international spread of Zika virus", and that there was "no public health justification" for postponing them.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Some athletes did not attend the Games because of the epidemic.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] On 2 September 2016, however, the World Health Organization reported that there were no confirmed cases of Zika among athletes or visitors during the 2016 Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The Guanabara Bay, whose waters were used for sailing and windsurfing competitions, is heavily polluted.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Among the chief causes of the pollution are uncollected trash fed into the bay via polluted rivers and slums along the coast.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Pollution of the Guanabara has been a long-term issue.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] At the Earth Summit in 1992, officials promised they would begin to address the pollution, but previous attempts to do so have been insufficient.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] As an aspect of their bid for the Games, Rio once again committed to making efforts towards cleaning the bay.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] However, some of these proposed initiatives have faced budgetary issues.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Prior to these efforts, only 17% of Rio's sewage was treated; this raw sewage also leaked into the bay.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Although Rio mayor Eduardo Paes stated that the city might not be able to reach its goal of having 80% of sewage treated, at least 60% of sewage was treated by March 2016, with a projected goal of 65% of sewage being treated by the start of the Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Rio's crime problems also received renewed attention after it was awarded the 2016 Games; mayor Paes stated that the city was facing "big issues" in heightening security, but that such concerns and issues were presented to the IOC throughout the bidding process.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The governor of Rio de Janeiro also highlighted the fact that London faced security problems, with a terrorist attack occurring just a day after it was awarded the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The estimate was that 5,000 men of the National Public Security Force and 22,000 military officers (14,800 Army; 5,900 Navy and 1,300 of the Brazilian Air Force), in addition to the fixed quota of Rio January, would act during the Olympic Games.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] On 21 July 2016, two weeks before the scheduled start of the Games, the Brazilian Federal Police broke up an Islamic jihadist terrorist cell named Ansar al-Khilafah Brazil by arresting 12 people.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In December 2014, media attention began growing when German broadcaster ARD reported on state-sponsored doping in Russia, comparing it to doping in East Germany.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In November 2015, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) published a report, and the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) suspended Russia indefinitely from world track and field events.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The United Kingdom Anti-Doping agency later assisted WADA with testing in Russia.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In June 2016, they reported they were unable to fully carry out their work, and noted intimidation by armed Federal Security Service (FSB) agents.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In response to these findings, WADA announced that RUSADA should be regarded as non-compliant with respect to the World Anti-Doping Code, and recommended that Russia be banned from competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] The IOC rejected the recommendation, stating that the IOC and each sport's international federation would make decisions on each athlete's individual basis.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] A day before the opening ceremony, 278 athletes were cleared to compete under the Russian flag, while 111 were removed because of doping.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] In contrast, the entire Kuwaiti team was banned from competing under their own flag for a non-doping related matter.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/2016-rio-de-janeiro-olympics-p02] Unlike the IOC, the International Paralympic Committee voted unanimously to ban the entire Russian team from the 2016 Summer Paralympics, and suspended the Russian Paralympic Committee after it found evidence that the DPM was also in operation at the 2014 Winter Paralympics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Gary Anderson Graduate School of Management** is a part of the UCR School of Business located at the University of California, Riverside.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Current offerings include MBA, Ph.D., Master of Finance and Master of Professional Accountancy (MPAc) programs.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] UCR first established the Graduation School of Administration in 1970.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] The school was subsequently renamed the Graduate School of Management in 1982.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Gary Anderson Family Foundation donated $5 million to the school, which was renamed the A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Gary Anderson Graduate School of Management.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] In 2008, the school was renamed the School of Business, housing both the undergraduate business program and the A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Gary Anderson Graduate School of Management, the MBA program enrolls about 80 students per year as of 2011.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] In 2010, MBA student interns participated in the first ever study of foreign direct investment in Riverside County.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] They worked with the Office of Foreign Trade at the Riverside County Economic Development Agency.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] The program is interdisciplinary, focusing on management and marketing.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] The first cohort is composed of six students.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] A Master of Professional Accountancy (MPAc) program was approved for launch in Fall 2012.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] In 2009, SoBA launched an Executive MBA program.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Typical applicants to the 21-month program have seven to 10 years of career experience minimum.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] The first cohort was composed of managers in finance, distribution, a CPA, and physicians.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] The program enrolls about 20-25 students per year.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] Students meet on alternating weekends at the UCR Palm Desert Graduate Center, and are required to attend a week-long residency and an international study trip.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] The Anderson School was ranked 90th in Best Business School, and the part-time MBA program was ranked 73th by *U.S.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-gary-anderson-graduate-school-of-management] It was listed in the *Princeton Reviews's Best Business Schools (West)* in 2023.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The corporation was formed when Belo Corporation separated its broadcasting and publishing operations into two corporations (with the broadcasting division going to the "old" Belo; it was later purchased by Gannett, and its former assets are part of what is now Tegna).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Headquartered in the Belo Building in Downtown Dallas, its CEO is James Moroney III.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] It also owns a part interest in Classified Ventures.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The company was organized as a fully owned subsidiary of Belo Corporation on October 1, 2007, then taken public by issuing the new stock to Belo shareholders and starting trade on February 8, 2008.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The split was structured so that Belo Corporation was the legal successor of the original company.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] While technically this corporate entity was formed in 2008, the organization traces its roots and history back to 1842.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Belo name from 1926 to 2002 when it was shortened to simply Belo.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] In 2016, the company announced that it is planning to leave the Belo Building for The Statler Library, also located downtown.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] As of 2018, the company website lists 1954 Commerce Street in Dallas as their headquarters address.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The company changed its name and ticker symbol and moved from the New York Stock Exchange to the Nasdaq on June 29, 2021, after acknowledging the history tied to their founder, A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Belo, a colonel in the Confederate military during the American Civil War, especially given that the company has its origins as early as 1842.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The change was proposed in 2021 by CEO Robert W.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Decherd to embrace "the social justice movement underway in America." The name change was approved by company shareholders the same year, with 99% of votes cast.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] In July 2025, Hearst Communications announced it had agreed to purchase DallasNews for $14 a share.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The sale is expected to close at the 4th quarter of 2025.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] A few weeks later Alden Global Capital submitted a competing bid for $16.50 a share, which was rejected by the DallasNews board.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Alden then submitted a letter threatening to take their offer directly to DallasNews shareholders.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] On September 24, 2025, DallasNews Corporation announced that it had completed its merger with Hearst.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The company also formerly published the *Denton Record-Chronicle*, *The Providence Journal*, the *Riverside Press-Enterprise*, *Quick*, a free weekly in Dallas, and *The Business Press*, a weekly business publication in Riverside.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Belo subsidiary, was the owner of *The Dallas Morning News* as well as other newspapers in the suburban Dallas area.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Belo acquired seven newspapers in 1963, which included *The Garland Daily News*, *The Grand Prairie Daily News*, and *The Richardson Daily News*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] The newspaper group would become Dallas-Fort Worth Suburban Newspapers, Inc.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] These newspapers would operate and be published relatively independently until the late 1980s.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-h-belo] Under increased advertising pressures and laws prohibiting media monopolies in urban markets, the newspapers were ultimately absorbed into *The Dallas Morning News*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones was born in Kansas City, Missouri, in 1913.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] He was raised in the city of Gardena in Southern California, but finished high school in Seattle.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Afterwards he enrolled in the University of Washington program in architecture, where he was particularly influenced by faculty member Lionel Pries, and graduated with Bachelor of Architecture (B.Arch.) in 1936.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] After marrying a fellow architecture student (Ruth Schneider), Jones returned to Los Angeles, working first in the offices of the modernist architects Douglas Honnold and George Vernon Russell from 1936 to 1937, and Burton A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] He worked for Allied Engineers, Inc. of San Pedro from 1940 to 1942, where he met the architect Frederick Emmons, with whom he would later partner.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones was responsible for the development and layout of Roosevelt Base in San Pedro and the Naval Reserve Air Base in Los Alamitos.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] In 1942, Jones received his California architect certification, divorced and received a commission as a lieutenant commander in the United States Navy.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] He was assigned to the aircraft carrier USS *Lexington*, which was serving in the Pacific theater.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Discharged from the Navy in 1945, Jones returned to Los Angeles and opened an architectural office in one of the two buildings of the house in Laurel Canyon he had built with his former wife.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] On his first day in business Jones had secured his first client.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] The years after the war saw Jones partnering with Paul R.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Williams on several projects in the Palm Springs area.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] These include the Palm Springs Tennis Club (1947), the Town & Country restaurant (1948), and the restaurant Romanoff's On the Rocks (1950).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones also participated in John Entenza's Case Study House program.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] The December 1950 issue of the magazine *Architectural Forum* featured a "Builder's House of the Year" designed by A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] The same issue also awarded the innovative Palo Alto building magnate Joseph Eichler "Subdivision of the Year".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Eichler then invited Jones to tour the Palo Alto development he had just completed where he suggested to Jones that the Builder of the Year join forces with the Architect of the Year.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] This relationship continued until Eichler's death in 1974.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] It was through this relationship that Jones was provided both the venue and the freedom to implement his concepts of incorporating park-like common areas in tract housing developments.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] His were some of the first greenbelts incorporated into moderate income tract housing in the United States.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] In 1960, Jones was hired by William Pereira as a planning partner in the development of the city of Irvine, California, which has since become a model for the integration of greenbelts into urban development.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] The Eichler commission prompted Jones to form a partnership with his prewar acquaintance, architect Frederick Emmons.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] The Jones and Emmons partnership lasted from 1951 until Emmons' retirement in 1969.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Their designs are reflected in some 5,000 of Eichler's homes, by Emmons' estimate.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones and Emmons were awarded national AIA Firm of the Year in 1969.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones was also a professor and later dean of architecture in the USC School of Architecture at the University of Southern California from 1951 until his death in 1979.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] By the 1960s Jones was designing a number of university campus buildings and larger office buildings, including the 1963 IBM Aerospace Headquarters in Westchester, California.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Several University of California campuses feature significant examples of Jones' work.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] In 1966, Jones designed "Sunnylands," the 200 acre (2.6 km2) estate and 32,000 square foot (3,000 m2) home of Walter Annenberg in Rancho Mirage, California.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones raised the tract house in California from the simple stucco box to a logically designed structure integrated into the landscape and surrounded by greenbelts.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] He introduced new materials as well as a new way of living within the built environment and popularized an informal, outdoor-oriented open plan.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] More than just abstractions of the suburban ranch house, most Jones and Emmons designs incorporated a usable atrium, high ceilings, post-and-beam construction and walls of glass.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] For the postwar moderate-income family, his work bridged the gap between custom-built and developer-built homes.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones often took advantage of industrial prefabricated units to provide affordable yet refined architecture.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] His larger buildings brought innovations to the integration of mechanical systems, improving their efficiency and maximizing retrievable space.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Jones' aesthetic style, precise detailing and siting made his buildings quintessential embodiments of mid-century American architecture.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] In 2013, a Hammer Museum exhibition entitled "A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Quincy Jones: Building for Better Living," redressed what curators had until then considered a major omission in the history of Los Angeles Modernism.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] An exhibition catalogue, now out of print, was published at the same time.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/a-quincy-jones] Several of his buildings are listed by the Los Angeles Conservancy.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] An **academic major** is the academic discipline to which an undergraduate student formally commits.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] A student who successfully completes all courses required for the major qualifies for an undergraduate degree.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] The word *major* (also called *concentration*, particularly at private colleges) is also sometimes used administratively to refer to the academic discipline pursued by a graduate student or postgraduate student in a master's or doctoral program.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] An academic major typically involves completion of a combination of required and elective courses in the chosen discipline.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] The latitude a student has in choosing courses varies from program to program.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] An academic major is administered by select faculty in an academic department.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] A major administered by more than one academic department is called an *interdisciplinary major*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] In some settings, students may be permitted to design their own major, subject to faculty approval.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] In the United States, students are usually not required to choose their major discipline when first enrolling as an undergraduate.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] In addition, most colleges and universities require that all students take a general core curriculum in the liberal arts.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Normally students are required to commit by the end of their second academic year at latest, and some schools even disallow students from declaring a major until this time.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] A student who declares two academic majors is said to have a *double major*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] A *coordinate major* is an ancillary major designed to complement the primary one.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] A coordinate major requires fewer course credits to complete.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Many colleges also allow students to declare a minor field, a secondary discipline in which they also take a substantial number of classes, but not so many as would be necessary to complete a major.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] The roots of the academic major as we now know it first surfaced in the 19th century as "alternative components of the undergraduate degree".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Before that, all students receiving an undergraduate degree would be required to study the same slate of courses geared at a comprehensive "liberal education".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] In 1825, the University of Virginia initiated an educational approach that would allow students to choose from an area of focus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Offering eight options (which included ancient languages, anatomy, medicine), other higher educational systems in Europe began to develop into a stricter specialization approach to studies after the American Civil War.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] In the United States, in the second half of the 19th century, concentrated foci at the undergraduate level began to prosper and popularize, but the familiar term "major" did not appear until 1877 in a Johns Hopkins University catalogue.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] The major generally required 2 years of study, while the minor required one.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] From 1880 to 1910, Baccalaureate granting American institutions vastly embraced a free-elective system, where students were endowed with a greater freedom to explore intellectual curiosities.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] The 1930s witnessed the appearance of first interdisciplinary major: American studies.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Culture was the grounding concept and orchestrating principle for its courses.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] 1960s to 1970s experienced a new tide of interdisciplinary majors and a relaxation of curriculum and graduation requirements.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] The academic major is considered a defining and dominant characteristic of the undergraduate degree.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] While general education is considered to be the breadth component of an undergraduate education, the major is commonly deemed the depth aspect.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Choice of major has a significant impact on employment prospects and lifetime earnings.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Through its development, scholars, academics, and educators have disagreed on the purpose and nature of the undergraduate major.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] In many universities, an **academic concentration** is a focus within a specific academic major, that is a field of study within a specific academic major.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] At several art schools and liberal arts colleges, an academic concentration serves a similar function to an academic minor at other universities, that is an academic discipline outside of the student's academic major in which they take a number of classes.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] At Brown University and Harvard University, however, the term "concentration" refers simply to the major field.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] At the doctoral studies level, an academic major or major field refers to a student's primary focus within their degree program while a minor or minor field refers to their secondary focus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] For example, a doctoral student studying history might pursue their degree in history with a major field in war and society and a minor field in postcolonial studies.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] An impacted major is a major for which more students apply for than the school can accommodate, a classic example of demand exceeding supply.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] When that occurs, the major becomes "impacted" and so is susceptible to higher standards of admission.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] For example, suppose that a school has minimum requirements are SATs of 1100 and a GPA of 3.0.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] If a person applies to an impacted major, the school can raise the minimum requirements as much as needed to weed out the students that it is unable to accommodate.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] Because of this, some students may opt to apply to a school as "Undeclared".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] If in the above example the school implements requirements of SATs of 1300 and a GPA of 3.4 for the impacted major, a student may find it better to apply as "Undeclared" if they meet only the minimum requirements.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-major] However, many universities, such as the University of California, Berkeley, may in turn present more difficult requirements (such as a GPA requirement in certain prerequisite classes) to enter an impacted major even once accepted to the university overall.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] The **Academic Performance Index** (**API**) was a measurement of academic performance and progress of individual schools in California, United States.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] The API was one of the main components of the Public Schools Accountability Act passed by the California State Legislature in 1999.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] It was last updated for the 2012–2013 school year, and on March 15, 2017, the California State Board of Education and the California Department of Education launched a new accountability system to replace the Academic Performance Index to better measure California's education goals.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] The replacement reporting interface is the California School Dashboard.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] A numeric API score ranged from a low of 200 to a high of 1000.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] The interim statewide API performance target for all schools was 800.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] A school's growth was measured by how well it was moving toward or past that goal.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] An API score was calculated for all students in a school as well as numerous API scores for each subgroup at the school (such as by race, English Learner Status, students with disabilities, and socioeconomically disadvantaged pupils).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] Each rank ranged from 1 to 10, with a score of 10 meaning that the school's API fell into the top 10%.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] A school's score or placement on the API was designed to be an indicator of a school's performance level and was calculated annually by the California Department of Education, primarily based on CST and CAHSEE tests.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] The API was closely tied to monetary and incentive awards by setting Annual Percent Growth Targets for each school and whether the school met or exceeded this goal.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] The Public Schools Accountability Act also established The Immediate Intervention/Underperforming Schools Program and the Governor's High Achieving/Improving Schools Program.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-performance-index] In addition, the API was used to determine Adequate Yearly Progress as a part of the No Child Left Behind Act.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The **University of California, Riverside** (**UCR** or **UC Riverside**) is a public land-grant research university in Riverside, California, United States.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It is one of the ten campuses of the University of California system.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The main campus sits on 1,900 acres (769 ha) in a suburban district of Riverside with a branch campus of 20 acres (8 ha) in Palm Desert.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 1907, the predecessor to UCR was founded as the UC Citrus Experiment Station, which conducted research in biological pest control and the use of growth regulators.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's undergraduate College of Letters and Science opened in 1954.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Regents of the University of California declared UCR a general campus of the system in 1959, and graduate students were admitted in 1961.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] To accommodate an enrollment of 21,000 students by 2015, more than $730 million has been invested in new construction projects since 1999.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR plans to have 35,000 students by 2035.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Preliminary accreditation of the UC Riverside School of Medicine was granted in October 2012 and the first class of 50 students was enrolled in August 2013.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It is the first new research-based public medical school in 40 years.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR is a member of the Association of American Universities.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 2000, UC Riverside was classified as an "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity." UCR's sports teams are known as the Highlanders and play in the Big West Conference of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Their nickname was inspired by the high altitude of the campus, which lies on the foothills of Box Springs Mountain.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] At the turn of the 20th century, Southern California was a major producer of citrus, the region's primary agricultural export.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The industry developed from the country's first navel orange trees, planted in Riverside in 1873.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Lobbied by the citrus industry, the UC Regents established the UC Citrus Experiment Station (CES) on February 14, 1907, on 23 acres (9 ha) of land on the east slope of Mount Rubidoux in Riverside.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The station conducted experiments in fertilization, irrigation and crop improvement.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 1917, the station was moved to a larger site, 475 acres (192 ha) near Box Springs Mountain.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The 1944 passage of the GI Bill during World War II set in motion a rise in college enrollments that necessitated an expansion of the state university system in California.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] A local group of citrus growers and civic leaders, including many UC Berkeley alumni, lobbied aggressively for a UC-administered liberal arts college next to the CES.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Dilworth authored Senate Bill 512 (1949) which former Assemblyman Philip L.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Boyd and Assemblyman John Babbage (both of Riverside) were instrumental in shepherding through the State Legislature.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Governor Earl Warren signed the bill in 1949, allocating $2 million for initial campus construction.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Watkins, dean of the UCLA College of Letters and Science, became the first provost of the new college at Riverside.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Initially conceived of as a small college devoted to the liberal arts, he ordered the campus built for a maximum of 1,500 students and recruited many young junior faculty to fill teaching positions.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's enrollment exceeded 1,000 students by the time Clark Kerr became president of the UC system in 1958.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Anticipating a "tidal wave" in enrollment growth required by the baby boom generation, Kerr developed the California Master Plan for Higher Education and the regents designated Riverside a general university campus in 1959.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's first chancellor, Herman Theodore Spieth, oversaw the beginnings of the school's transition to a full university and its expansion to a capacity of 5,000 students.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's second chancellor, Ivan Hinderaker led the campus through the era of the free speech movement and kept student protests peaceful in Riverside.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] According to a 1998 interview with Hinderaker, the city of Riverside received negative press coverage for smog after the mayor asked Governor Ronald Reagan to declare the South Coast Air Basin a disaster area in 1971; subsequent student enrollment declined by up to 25% through 1979.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Hinderaker's development of innovative programs in business administration and biomedical sciences created incentive for enough students to enroll at Riverside to keep the campus open.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In the 1990s, UC experienced a new surge of enrollment applications, now known as "Tidal Wave II".
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The regents targeted UCR for an annual growth rate of 6.3%, the fastest in the UC system, and anticipated 19,900 students at UCR by 2010.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] By 1995, African American, American Indian, and Latino student enrollments accounted for 30% of the UCR student body, the highest proportion of any UC campus at the time.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The 1997 implementation of Proposition 209—which banned the use of affirmative action by state agencies—reduced the ethnic diversity at the more selective UC campuses but further increased it at UCR.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] With UCR scheduled for dramatic population growth, efforts have been made to increase its popular and academic recognition.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The students voted for a fee increase to move UCR athletics into NCAA Division I standing in 1998.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In the 1990s, proposals were made to establish a law school, a medical school, and a school of public policy at UCR, with the UCR School of Medicine and the School of Public Policy becoming reality in 2012.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In June 2006, UCR received its largest gift, 15.5 million from two local couples, in trust towards building its medical school.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The regents formally approved UCR's medical school proposal in 2006.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Upon its completion in 2013, it was the first new medical school built in California in 40 years.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Panoramic view of campus from the Box Springs Mountains (north to the right).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Student housing is to the far lower right, west of which are the athletic facilities.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The agricultural fields in the central left are designated for future campus development (2007).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] East Campus, occupying approximately 600 acres (243 ha), hosts the core cluster of academic buildings and services.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The original buildings that formed the earliest kernel of the campus included the UC Citrus Experiment Station, residential buildings, and barn, all of which are still in use.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Built by 1917 at a cost of $165,000, the architecture of the major buildings followed the Mission Revival style suggesting the Spanish colonial heritage of Southern California.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Further major construction largely ceased on the site until the groundbreaking for the College of Humanities Arts and Social Sciences (CHASS) in April 1951.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] A group of five buildings designed by different architects in a decidedly more Modern style were completed by 1954: the Rivera Library, Webber Hall, Geology Building, Physical Education Building and Watkins Hall.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] After the Regents declared UCR a "general campus" of the UC system in 1958, many new buildings and additions were laid out over the following decade.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Following an east–west axis, new student residence halls and athletic facilities were developed along the southeastern quadrant of the main campus, while academic and research facilities were built along the central campus area closer to the freeway.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Bell Tower, one of only five carillons in California, was built in this period.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Quincy Jones, the tower is 161 ft (49 m) tall and contains 48 bells, each weighing from 28 pounds (13 kg) to 5,091 pounds (2,309 kg), covering four chromatic octaves.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] After the drop in enrollment and subsequent restructuring of academic programs in the 1970s, little capacity construction was undertaken over the next two decades.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] However, enrollment growth in the late 1980s justified considerable further campus expansion over the 1990s.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Major additions built in the period include: Bourns Hall, completed in 1995; the Humanities & Social Science building, completed in 1996; and the Science Library, completed in 1998.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Pentland and Stonehaven residence halls were completed in 2000, and the Arts building was completed in 2001.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Active construction projects include the "Multidisciplinary Research Building," new residence halls located east of A-I and ongoing renovations to Pierce Hall.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The first phase of a new Commons was completed in 2007, and phase II is in development.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Other ongoing projects include a new CHASS Instructional and Research Center and Students Academic Support Services Building.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Since 1999, more than $730 million has been invested in construction projects.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Of the 511 acres (207 ha) of UCR property constituting West Campus, approximately 216 acres (87 ha) along University Avenue have been developed.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] These include facilities such as University Extension, the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) Germplasm Repository, International Village (student housing), Human Resources and Highlander Hall.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] University Village, a mixed use commercial development, features a movie theater, stores, restaurants, office space, and an apartment complex, along with a parking structure and surface parking.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Citrus groves and row crops occupy the remaining 295 acres (119 ha) stretching northwest to the intersection of Chicago Avenue and Le Conte Drive.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Plans for future expansion include converting a portion of these fields into new UCR infrastructure.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The University of California, Riverside has recently united its three downtown arts presentation venues under the umbrella name of the UCR ARTSblock.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The ARTSblock is composed of the UCR/California Museum of Photography, The Sweeney Art Gallery, and the Culver Center of the Arts, a media lab and presentation facility.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The three institutions reside side by side in the heart of downtown Riverside's historic pedestrian mall.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Heckmann International Center for Entrepreneurial Management was founded in Palm Desert in 2001.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] After the 540-acre (219 ha) Coachella Valley Agricultural Research Station, it is UCR's second institutional presence in the Coachella Valley.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Initially by a $6 million gift from Richard J.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Heckmann, a water treatment entrepreneur, the institution was planned as a teaching and research center of the A.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Gary Anderson Graduate School of Management at the UCR School of Business.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The center encourages local entrepreneurship through the Coachella Valley Angel Network, an angel investment network.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] A further investment of $10 million from the State of California and a donation of 20 acres (8 ha) of land from the City of Palm Desert allowed for the opening of an expanded graduate center on April 15, 2005, adjacent to the California State University, San Bernardino Palm Desert Campus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The center is also home to university researchers in conservation biology, technology transfer and Native American studies.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Master's level instruction in business management and creative writing is available at the center.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] As a campus of the University of California system, UCR is governed by a Board of Regents and administered by a president.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Drake, and the current chancellor of the university is S.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's academic policies are set by its Academic Senate, a legislative body composed of all UCR faculty members.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR is organized into three academic colleges, two professional schools, and two graduate schools.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's liberal arts college, the College of Humanities, Arts and Social Sciences, was founded in 1954, and began accepting graduate students in 1960.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The College of Natural and Agricultural Sciences, founded in 1958, incorporated the CES as part of the first research-oriented institution at UCR; it eventually also incorporated the natural science departments formerly associated with the liberal arts college to form its present structure in 1974.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's newest academic unit, the Bourns College of Engineering, was founded in 1989.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Comprising the professional schools are the Graduate School of Education, founded in 1968, and the UCR School of Business, founded in 1970.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] These units collectively provide 81 majors and 52 minors, 48 master's degree programs, and 42 Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) programs.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR is the only UC campus to offer undergraduate degrees in creative writing and public policy and one of three UCs (along with Berkeley and Irvine) to offer an undergraduate degree in business administration.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Through its Division of Biomedical Sciences, founded in 1974, UCR offers the Thomas Haider medical degree program in collaboration with UCLA.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's doctoral program in the emerging field of dance theory, founded in 1992, was the first program of its kind in the United States, and UCR's minor in lesbian, gay and bisexual studies, established in 1996, was the first undergraduate program of its kind in the UC system.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] A new BA program in bagpipes was inaugurated in 2007.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Institutional rankings of UC Riverside vary widely, depending on the criteria of the publication.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] News & World Report* has named UC Riverside the top university in the nation for social mobility 7 years running.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In the 2026 edition of the *Washington Monthly* college rankings, UCR ranked 50th among national universities.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] *Washington Monthly* assesses the quality of schools based on social mobility (recruiting and graduating low-income students), research (producing cutting-edge scholarship and PhDs), and service (encouraging students to give something back to their country).
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Since 1997, more than 110 UCR faculty members have been elected fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Over the course of UCR's history, seven current or former faculty members have been elected to the National Academy of Sciences, and more than 50 have received Guggenheim Fellowships.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR currently has two Nobel laureates on its faculty.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR operated under a $727 million budget in fiscal year 2014–15.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The state government provided $214 million, student fees accounted for $224 million and $100 million came from contracts and grants.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Private support and other sources accounted for the remaining $189 million.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Overall, monies spent at UCR have an economic impact of nearly $1 billion in California.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR research expenditure in FY 2018 totaled $167.8 million.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Total research expenditures at Riverside are significantly concentrated in agricultural science, accounting for 53% of total research expenditures spent by the university in 2002.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Top research centers by expenditure, as measured in 2002, include the Agricultural Experiment Station, the Center for Environmental Research and Technology, the Center for Bibliographical Studies, the Air Pollution Research Center, and the Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Throughout UCR's history, researchers have developed more than 40 new citrus varieties and invented new techniques to help the $960 million-a-year California citrus industry fight pests and diseases.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 1927, entomologists at the CES introduced two wasps from Australia as natural enemies of a major citrus pest, the citrophilus mealybug, saving growers in Orange County $1 million in annual losses.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] This event was pivotal in establishing biological control as a practical means of reducing pest populations.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 1963, plant physiologist Charles Coggins proved that application of gibberellic acid allows fruit to remain on citrus trees for extended periods.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The ultimate result of his work, which continued through the 1980s, was the extension of the citrus-growing season in California from four to nine months.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 1980, UC Riverside released the Oroblanco grapefruit, its first patented citrus variety.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Since then, the citrus breeding program has released other varieties such as the Melogold grapefruit, the Gold Nugget mandarin (or tangerine), and others that have yet to be given trademark names.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] To assist entrepreneurs in developing new products, UCR is a primary partner in the Riverside Regional Technology Park, which includes the City of Riverside and the County of Riverside.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It also administers six reserves of the University of California Natural Reserve System.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR recently announced a partnership with China Agricultural University to launch a new center in Beijing, which will study ways to respond to the country's growing environmental issues.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR can also boast the birthplace of two name reactions in organic chemistry, the Castro-Stephens coupling and the Midland Alpine Borane Reduction.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Admission to UC Riverside is rated as "more selective" by *U.S.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The average GPA of the enrolled freshmen was 3.83, while the average SAT scores were 620 for reading & writing and 635 for math.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 2006, 43.4 percent of admitted students were first generation college students, 38.7 percent came from low family income backgrounds, and 24 percent graduated from low-performing high schools as measured by Academic Performance Index (API) scores.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] News* ranked UCR as the third most ethnically diverse and, by the number of undergraduates receiving Pell Grants (42 percent), the 15th most economically diverse student body in the nation.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] According to statistics released by the Education Trust, a national nonprofit, in 2005 UC Riverside graduated 65.3 percent of its students in six years, a figure consistent with national averages but behind the average set by the top five public research universities by as much as 22 percent.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] However, UCR's consistency with the national average is well above the median of 39 percent for low-income-serving institutions as calculated in 2006 by the National Center for Education Statistics, making the campus a model for successful approaches to diversity in higher education.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's varsity teams compete in the Big West Conference of NCAA Division I.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Programs include men's and women's soccer, cross country, basketball, track and field, baseball, softball, tennis, golf and women's volleyball.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] After students voted to assess themselves $35 a quarter to fund the athletic programs in 1998, men's and women's soccer and golf were added, and the athletic department switched from NCAA Division II in 2000.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] While at Division II level, UCR produced 5 national championship teams in men's baseball and women's volleyball.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] As of 2006, UCR had produced 17 individual national champions, 17 All-Americans and many conference and regional champions.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The men's golf team represented UCR in the 2004 and 2005 NCAA West Regionals after winning back-to-back Conference Championships in those respective years while having three athletes ranked in the top 100 in the country.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 2006, 2007, and 2010 the UCR women's basketball team represented the conference in the Division I tournament but lost all three times in the first round.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In December 2008, the UCR women's basketball team upset the #16-seeded Vanderbilt Commodores.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Total library collections at UCR comprise more than 2 million volumes, 14,017 electronic journals, 23,000 serial subscriptions, and 1.7 million microformats.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Two large, four-story libraries house most of the physical collections.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The 179,595 ft (54,741 m) Rivera library was constructed in 1954 and named after Tomás Rivera in 1985.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It seats a capacity of 956 and houses general humanities and social science collections, as well as special collections, including the world's largest collection of science fiction, horror and fantasy literature, the 110,000-volume Eaton Collection.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Rivera Library also hosts the only U.S.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Patent and Trademark Depository based on a UC campus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Orbach Science Library, built in 1998, seats a capacity of 1,360 and houses 533,000 volumes in the physical, natural, agricultural, biomedical, engineering and computer sciences, with special strengths in the areas of citrus and sub-tropical horticulture, entomology, and arid lands agriculture.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] On November 3, 2009, the Science library was officially renamed the Raymond L.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Orbach Science Library in honor of former chancellor Raymond L.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Smaller libraries include the Media and Cultural Library, the Music Library, and a branch digital library in Palm Desert.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The UCR Library is one of 116 members of the Association of Research Libraries, and is ranked 93rd in this group.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's academic colleges administer significant museum collections in the arts and sciences.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Citrus Variety Collection constitutes 1,800 trees representing two of each of the 640 types of citrus and 28 other related genera in the family Rutaceae, the largest such collection in the world.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Herbarium houses more than 110,000 dried plant specimens from across the Western hemisphere.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR is also home to 40 acres (16 ha) of botanical gardens containing more than 3,500 plant species from around the world.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Gardens are located in the eastern foothills of the Box Springs Mountain on the University of California, Riverside campus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Over four miles (6 km) of trails wind through many microclimates and hilly terrain.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Entomology Research Museum contains more than four million insect specimens, with particular strengths in Hymenoptera, Chalcidoidea, Aphelinidae, Thysanoptera and Meloidae.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The UCR/California Museum of Photography and Sweeney Art Gallery house UCR's primary art collections.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The UCR/CMP includes the world's largest holding of vintage stereographs, one of the three great public collections of photographic apparatus in the US, and the University Print Collection of contemporary and historical images by over 1000 photographers.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Located adjacent to the UCR/CMP, the Sweeney Art Gallery holds approximately 650 unique works, with especially strong collections from the modern to contemporary periods, including pieces by Alexander Calder, Roy Lichtenstein, Millard Sheets and Kara Walker.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Riverside enrolls the highest percentage of African American students of any of the 10 UC campuses and the second highest percentage of Latino students after Merced, prompting the *Los Angeles Times* and *New York Times* to run stories stating that UCR is a "campus of choice" for minority students.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR was the first college in California to open a staffed lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) resource center in 1993; the first UC campus to offer an LGBT minor studies program in 1996; and the first campus in the nation to offer a gender-neutral housing option in 2005.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In recognition of this, *The Advocate* recognized UCR as one of the nation's best campuses for LGBT students in 2006, although it did not make the top 20.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The *Princeton Review* listed UCR as a "Best Western College." While over 83 percent of students are non-white, there is a tendency for the different ethnic groups to self-segregate.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's residence halls consist of four structures—Aberdeen-Inverness, Dundee, Lothian, and Pentland Hills—which can house over 3,000 students in single, double, and triple rooms.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In addition, UCR features several on-campus apartment complexes such as Stonehaven, Bannockburn Village, University Plaza, Falkirk, Oban, Glen Mor and International Village, which together house 959 students.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Oban has since been upgraded to accommodate family housing following the demolition of Canyon Crest.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Glen Mor, an apartment housing complex adjacent to Pentland Hills, was opened in 2007, and the university also purchased a nearby apartment complex, which is now known as Falkirk, for student housing in 2007.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] About half of the student population lives in off-campus apartments, one-fourth commute, and one-fourth live on campus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Thirty percent of students remain on campus for the weekend.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Reflecting UCR's diversity, a number of residence halls have been established for specific social, cultural and academic needs.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR's three academic colleges in the humanities, sciences and engineering fields are represented by respective theme halls, and halls exist for honor students and transfer students.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In Fall 2018, UCR began construction of a new residence hall and dining facility in the parking lot behind Aberdeen-Inverness.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] This new residence hall and dining facility opened as Dundee-Glasgow in 2020, and features UCR's first two-story residential restaurant.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR hosts over 500 registered student organizations, including the Associated Students of the University of California, Riverside (ASUCR), which represents undergraduates on administrative and policy issues.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Membership is composed of all UCR students who pay mandatory activity fees.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] ASUCR assesses these fees and distributes funds to registered student groups on campus, including student lobbying groups, a right that ASUCR won in a federal court case against the regents in 1999.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Of the registered student groups, 40 are fraternities and sororities.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Thirteen percent of the undergraduate student body participates in Greek life, although chapter houses are not permitted.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Including the Greek letter organizations, more than 60 student volunteer service organizations at UCR contribute to more than 100,000 hours of collective and individual service done in the community each year.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Jewish student life has existed for over a decade through UCR Hillel.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Student media organizations include *The Highlander* student newspaper, currently published every Tuesday during the academic year.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] First published in 1954, *The Highlander* remains an independent student media outlet.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It was an entirely self-funded organization until 2001, when ASUCR passed a funding referendum for it.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Student fees from the referendum go towards overhead and printing costs, however *The Highlander* is primarily funded through its own advertising revenue.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] In 2003, *The Highlander* published a comic depicting a stereotypical Asian American graduate teaching assistant with poor English skills, inciting community backlash and prompting an apology from Editor-in-Chief Kahlil Ford.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Other student news publications on campus include the *Asian Community Times, Indian Time, Nuestra Cosa, Queeriosity*, and the *X-Factor Student Newspaper*.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] Campus literary magazines include *Mosaic*, published at UCR since 1959, and *Crate,* published by graduate students in UCR's master's level creative writing program since 2005.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] UCR broadcasts over radio as KUCR at 88.3 FM.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The station programs a variety of independent music, news and commentary.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] On-campus entertainment events are planned by a 14-member Associated Students Program Board (ASPB), comprising six student-run divisions that include concerts, films and lectures, cultural events and special events, as well as a marketing and leadership division.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] ASPB's major events include the Block Party Concert, Winter Soulstice, Homecoming Bonfire and Spring Splash.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] The Graduate Student Association of the University of California, Riverside (GSAUCR) is ASUCR's counterpart on the graduate level.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It is guided by a Graduate Student Council consisting of representatives from every department on campus.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] GSAUCR assesses fees required of all graduate students and uses them to fund research awards and colloquiums, conference travel grants, and speaker funds.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] More than 94,000 alumni have graduated from UCR over the course of its history.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] A 13,865-square-foot (1,288.1 m2) Alumni and Visitors Center was established in 2007.
[src:university-of-california-riverside/university-of-california-riverside] It is used as a central gathering place for alumni and holds several facilities for use including meeting rooms, a formal board room, a central lobby area, a library, several alumni affairs offices, and a café.
